[[File:Ali Erturk portrait.jpg|thumb|Ali Erturk]] '''Ali Erturk''' (born September 1980) is a [[Turkey|Turkish]] [[neuroscientist]], inventor, and artist living in Munich, Germany. After his undergraduate study at [[Bilkent University]] in Ankara, he joined [[Max Planck Institute of Neurobiology|Max-Planck-Institute for Neurobiology]] for his PhD and [[Genentech|Genentech Inc.]] for postdoctoral research.
His is known for invention of [[3DISCO|DISCO]] tissue transparency technology<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ertürk|first=Ali|last2=Mauch|first2=Christoph P|last3=Hellal|first3=Farida|last4=Förstner|first4=Friedrich|last5=Keck|first5=Tara|last6=Becker|first6=Klaus|last7=Jährling|first7=Nina|last8=Steffens|first8=Heinz|last9=Richter|first9=Melanie|date=January 2012|title=Three-dimensional imaging of the unsectioned adult spinal cord to assess axon regeneration and glial responses after injury|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nm.2600|journal=Nature Medicine|volume=18|issue=1|pages=166–171|doi=10.1038/nm.2600|issn=1546-170X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ertürk|first=Ali|last2=Becker|first2=Klaus|last3=Jährling|first3=Nina|last4=Mauch|first4=Christoph P|last5=Hojer|first5=Caroline D|last6=Egen|first6=Jackson G|last7=Hellal|first7=Farida|last8=Bradke|first8=Frank|last9=Sheng|first9=Morgan|date=November 2012|title=Three-dimensional imaging of solvent-cleared organs using 3DISCO|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nprot.2012.119|journal=Nature Protocols|volume=7|issue=11|pages=1983–1995|doi=10.1038/nprot.2012.119|issn=1750-2799}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pan|first=Chenchen|last2=Cai|first2=Ruiyao|last3=Quacquarelli|first3=Francesca Paola|last4=Ghasemigharagoz|first4=Alireza|last5=Lourbopoulos|first5=Athanasios|last6=Matryba|first6=Paweł|last7=Plesnila|first7=Nikolaus|last8=Dichgans|first8=Martin|last9=Hellal|first9=Farida|date=October 2016|title=Shrinkage-mediated imaging of entire organs and organisms using uDISCO|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nmeth.3964|journal=Nature Methods|volume=13|issue=10|pages=859–867|doi=10.1038/nmeth.3964|issn=1548-7105}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cai|first=Ruiyao|last2=Pan|first2=Chenchen|last3=Ghasemigharagoz|first3=Alireza|last4=Todorov|first4=Mihail I.|last5=Foerstera|first5=Benjamin|last6=Zhao|first6=Shan|last7=Bhatia|first7=Harsharan S.|last8=Mrowka|first8=Leander|last9=Theodorou|first9=Delphine|date=2018-07-23|title=Panoptic vDISCO imaging reveals neuronal connectivity, remote trauma effects and meningeal vessels in intact transparent mice|url=https://www.biorxiv.org/content/early/2018/07/23/374785|journal=bioRxiv|language=en|pages=374785|doi=10.1101/374785}}</ref> in biomedical research allowing to visualize intact neuronal networks in the brain and body.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/23/science/transparent-mouse-udisco-glow.html|title=Seeing Through to a Mouse’s Nervous System|last=Fleur|first=Nicholas St|date=2016-08-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-03-22|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-technique-shrinks-makes-whole-animals-transparent-1471878084|title=New Technique Shrinks, Makes Small Animals Transparent|last=Hernandez|first=Daniela|date=2016-08-22|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-03-22|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.de/transparent-mouse-udisco-2016-8/?r=US&IR=T|title=A 'revolutionary' new technology can turn mice clear — and might one day map your brain|work=Business Insider Deutschland|access-date=2018-03-22|language=de}}</ref> Since early 2015, he is leading the Acute Brain Injury<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://research.isd-muc.de/Acute_braininjury.html|title=ISD RESEARCH|last=weingart|first=antonia|website=research.isd-muc.de|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> research group at the [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://research.isd-muc.de/Acute_braininjury_PI.html|title=ISD RESEARCH|last=weingart|first=antonia|website=research.isd-muc.de|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> He is also an Adjunct Professor at [[University of Rochester]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.urmc.rochester.edu/labs/nedergaard/personnel.aspx|title=Personnel - Nedergaard Lab - University of Rochester Medical Center|website=www.urmc.rochester.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref>
