| | A small [[Scincomorpha|scincomorph]] lizard of otherwise uncertain evolutionary affinities.<ref name="foster-schilleria" /> It is the only lizard genus endemic to the Morrison Formation.<ref name="foster-schilleria" /> |- |}
==Mammaliaforms==
Many types of [[mammaliaform]] [[cynodonts]], mostly early [[Mammalia|mammals]], are known from the Morrison; almost all of them were small sized animals, though occupying a very large variety of ecological niches, from the more [[rodent]]-like [[multituberculate]]s to the carnivorous [[eutriconodont]]s (including the possibly volant ''[[Triconolestes]]'') to the [[anteater]]-like ''[[Fruitafossor]]''. Unclassified types include the digger ''[[Fruitafossor|Fruitafossor windscheffelia]]''. [[Docodonta|Docodonts]] included the common genus ''[[Docodon]]'', represented by ''D. victor'', ''D. striatus'', and ''D. superbus'', and ''[[Peraiocynodon]]'' sp. [[Multituberculata|Multituberculates]], a common type of early mammal, were represented by ''[[Ctenacodon|Ctenacodon serratus]]'', ''C. laticeps'', ''C. scindens'', ''[[Glirodon|Glirodon grandis]]'', ''[[Morrisonodon|Morrisonodon brentbaatar]]'', ''[[Psalodon|Psalodon fortis]]'', ''?P. marshi'', ''P. potens'', and ''[[Zofiabaatar|Zofiabaatar pulcher]]''. [[Triconodonta|Triconodonts]] present included ''[[Amphidon|Amphidon superstes]]'', ''[[Aploconodon|Aploconodon comoensis]]'', ''[[Conodon|Conodon gidleyi]]'', ''[[Priacodon|Priacodon ferox]]'', ''P. fruitaensis'', ''P. gradaevus'', ''P. lulli'', ''P. robustus'', ''[[Triconolestes|Triconolestes curvicuspis]]'', and ''[[Trioracodon|Trioracodon bisulcus]]''.
[[Tinodontidae|Tinodontids]] were represented by ''[[Eurylambia|Eurylambia aequicrurius]]'' (probably ''Tinodon''), and ''[[Tinodon|Tinodon bellus]]'' (including ''T. lepidus''). Finally, two families of [[Dryolestoidea]] were present: [[Paurodontidae]], including ''[[Comotherium|Comotherium richi]]'', ''[[Euthlastus|Euthlastus cordiformis]]'', ''[[Paurodon|Paurodon valens]]'', and ''[[Tathiodon|Tathiodon agilis]]''; and [[Dryolestidae]], including ''[[Amblotherium|Amblotherium gracilis]]'', ''[[Dryolestes|Dryolestes obtusus]]'' (common genus), ''D. priscus'', ''D. vorax'', ''[[Laolestes|Laolestes eminens]]'', ''L. grandis'', and ''[[Miccylotyrans|Miccylotyrans minimus]]''.
In [[2009 in paleontology|2009]], a study by J. R. Foster was published which estimated the body masses of mammals from the Morrison Formation by [[Regression analysis|using]] the ratio of dentary length to body mass of modern marsupials as a reference. Foster concludes that ''[[Docodon]]'' was the most massive mammaliaform genus of the formation at 141g and ''[[Fruitafossor]]'' was the least massive at 6g. The average Morrison mammal had a mass of 48.5g. A graph of the body mass distribution of Morrison mammal genera produced a [[right-skewed curve]], meaning that there were more low-mass genera.<ref name="foster2009">Foster, J.R. 2009. Preliminary body mass estimates for mammalian genera of the Morrison Formation (Upper Jurassic, North America). PaleoBios 28(3):114-122.</ref>
