'''Quantitative biology''' is an umbrella term encompassing the use of mathematical, statistical or computational techniques to study [[life]] and living [[organisms]]. The central theme and goal of quantitative biology is the creation of predictive models based on fundamental principles governing [[biological system|living systems]].<ref>{{cite journal | last=Howard | first=J. | title=Quantitative cell biology: the essential role of theory | journal=Molecular Biology of the Cell | publisher=American Society for Cell Biology (ASCB) | volume=25 | issue=22 | date=2014-11-03 | issn=1059-1524 | doi=10.1091/mbc.e14-02-0715 | pages=3438–3440| pmc=4230598 }}</ref><ref name="BioSciencep=511">{{cite journal | last=Hastings | first=Alan | last2=Arzberger | first2=Peter | last3=Bolker | first3=Ben | last4=Collins | first4=Scott | last5=Ives | first5=Anthony R. | last6=Johnson | first6=Norman A. | last7=Palmer | first7=Margaret A. | title=Quantitative Bioscience for the 21st Century | journal=BioScience | publisher=Oxford University Press (OUP) | volume=55 | issue=6 | year=2005 | issn=0006-3568 | doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2005)055[0511:QBFTSC]2.0.CO;2 | page=511}}</ref>
The subfields of biology that employ [[quantitative approach]]es include: * [[Mathematical and theoretical biology]] * [[Computational biology]] * [[Bioinformatics]] * [[Biostatistics]] * [[Systems biology]] * [[Synthetic biology]] * [[Epidemiology]]
